function countSubIslands(grid1, grid2) {
    function dfs(i, j) {
        if (i < 0 || i >= grid1.length || j < 0 || j >= grid1[0].length || grid2[i][j] === 0) {
            return true;
        }

        grid2[i][j] = 0;

        let isSubIsland = grid1[i][j] === 1;
        isSubIsland &= dfs(i + 1, j) ? 1 : 0;
        isSubIsland &= dfs(i - 1, j) ? 1 : 0;
        isSubIsland &= dfs(i, j + 1) ? 1 : 0;
        isSubIsland &= dfs(i, j - 1) ? 1 : 0;

        return isSubIsland;
    }

    let count = 0;

    for (let i = 0; i < grid1.length; i++) {
        for (let j = 0; j < grid1[0].length; j++) {
            if (grid2[i][j] === 1 && dfs(i, j)) {
                count++;
            }
        }
    }

    return count;
}
```

    The algorithm uses Depth-First Search (DFS) to traverse the islands in `grid2`. For each cell in `grid2` that has a value of 1 (representing land), it checks if it can be a sub-island by performing DFS.

Within the DFS search, if the corresponding cell in `grid1` has a value of 0, it indicates that the part of the island being traversed in `grid2` is not a subset of the island in `grid1`. In this case, the variable `isSubIsland` is set to `false`. During the search, it also marks the visited cells in `grid2` as 0 to avoid checking them multiple times. If the entire `dfs` returns `true`, then it is considered as a sub-island, and the count is incremented.

In the end, the total sub-island count is returned.

